 <br>
I see those who claim to be &quot;evil&quot; in a high elf's skin. Embrace the truth and cast off the powers you gained from dedication to a god of light and join us,then.<br>
 <br>
To do otherwise is to try to play both against the middle in your search for personal power. The rewards are great,in this world.<br>
 <br>
You will find them less so when you finally pass from the realm. No matter what you use to justify them,your acts will be judged by who you pledged to serve in the beginning.<br>
 <br>
There will be no mercy on your souls as a result. Not that Father Innoruuk even considers &quot;mercy&quot; worthy of contemplating,but he rewards the faithful and condemns the infidel.<br>
 <br>
I think the gods have a sense of humor. To create creatures of great power,they often take the spiritual remains of something of great power and twist it. The Father does this to even the weakest of failures,making the bitter dead that wander Nektulos and Kithicor.<br>
<br>
So many of them were as you were in life. You turned from your gods for power,not realizing that if they died still dedicated to the god they blaspheme....you will still go to them in the end.<br>
 <br>
Even Marr has no pity for the one who turns his coat. Tunare knows it is un-natural. The Tribunal sees it and passes judgement,as any who walk the planes know. <br>
 <br>
Your fate will not be glory,or legend. It will be as fodder to be slain and tormented again and again,since the only service you could provide in life was doing to same to your own...and perhaps if your god is more merciful than mine,you will not keep enough of yourself to know it.<br>
 <br>
The faithful gain their own rewards-indeed,the gods sent examples of these to many towns,to show that there is indeed great and better things for those who hold true to their gods. They are heroes. <br>
 <br>
You are faithless scum. The pale elven servant of Tunare that failed her goddess and instead slew what she would,never minding the balance? That &quot;corrupt,evil&quot; druid?<br>
 <br>
I enjoy killing you every time I see your dull,mindless cur of a beastly body wandering by in the Commonlands. I laugh more when I see your brothers and sisters do it. Some are respectful enough to thank their goddess for the gift. They would be more so if they knew how that wolf,that bear,or that cat came to be.<br>
 <br>
The others will eventually learn what it feels like. It is their fate.<br>
<br>
If you choose to follow a new path,devote yourself to it. Or join them.<br>
